1.Nf3 g6 2.d4 Bg7 3.g3 d6 4.Bg2 Nf6 5.O-O O-O 6.c4 Nbd7 7.Nc3 e5 8.e4 c6 9.h3 {AMY aor sae re note Preventing ...Af6-g4, one of Black’s common tricks, before placing the dark-squared bishop on e3. Upon coming to the United States, Wojo would begin to use the more subtle move order 9. £b1 in order to prevent the possibility mentioned in the note to Black’s next move. The move 9. #b1 is featured in the next game. De NWN Vi N Iw} 9...Qe7 {This is too passive. The more ambi- tious 9... %b6 is Black’s best attempt, after which White can choose from among} 10.Re1 { (Wojo’s usual choice) , 10. d5, and the crazy 10. c5. In Chapter 5, which goes over various move or- ders, we also examine one of Dean’s favorite lines here, 10. 2b1!?. 10. 2e3 It is worth noting at this point that there exists a huge misconception among club players that White’s dark- squared bishop belongs on the long di- agonal and that he should fianchetto it with b2-b3 and 2c1-b2. Although such a plan is still occasionally employed at grandmaster level, it is not White’s best idea in this position. Black is aiming to play ...exd4 and open the center, so White should be seeking to neutralize Black’s control of the a1-h8 diagonal by stepping off it — not by adding pieces to it for Black’s g7-bishop to attack. From the position in the previous dia- gram, the e3 square is almost always the best one for White’s own dark- squared bishop. From there, it eyes the queenside (particularly the vulnerable b6 square) and discourages skirmishes such as ...%d8-b6-b4. Furthermore, should Black become ambitious and try ...7-h5-h4 to take a potshot at White’s kingside, it would help to be able to post the clergyman to the g5 square. Wojo sometimes developed the bishop to {4 in order to provoke Black into wasting time (such as with ...Af6-h5) , but ultimately the bishop was usually relocated to e3. It is hard to say exactly why so many players choose to fianchetto the dark-squared bishop as White in these structures, but perhaps it has to do with a psychological defect of some sort. White players take comfort in devel- oping both bishops to their respective long diagonals, and feel they are “coun- tering” Black’s dark-squared bishop on g7 by placing their own on b2. One look at Bronstein and Neat’s 1999 work Play the King’s Indian ought to cure any player of White of this attitude. The authors pick games featuring White’s dark-squared bishop developing to b2 in order to demonstrate the potential of Black’s position — for instance, in one game (L.Pachman-Bronstein, Prague 1946) , Black even managed an effective ...4a8x (2) al exchange sacrifice: r7i0 wae mer ‘a an Ail U7 20... xal! 21. 8xal &xd4 22. 8xd4 Axb3 23. 8xd6 Wxf2! (Bronstein gives 23... 0xal 24. 0d5 Wxf2 25. 0f6+ and 26. 0xe8) 24. 8a2 Wxg3+ 25. eh1 Yxc3 26. 8a3 2xh3 27. Bxb3 2xg2+ 28. hoxg2 Yxc4 29. 8d4 We6 30. 8xb7 Ha8 31. We2 h3+ 0-1. Of course, this doesn’t mean that White should never develop his dark- squared bishop to b2 in the Fianchetto King’s Indian. There are plenty of situations where b3 and 2b2 are ap- propriate. In general, however, they occur only in variations such as the Panno (with an early ...Ac6, ...a6, and ..4b8 from Black) , when the second player isn’t particularly aiming for a quick ...e7-e5xd4. And with that, let’s return to the game.} 10...Re8 11.Qc2 {Reinforcing the e4-pawn and con- necting White’s rooks.} 11...exd4 12.Nxd4 Nc5 13.Bf1 {?OCR} {White defendsthe pawn on e4 indi- rectly. This is better than 13. f3, which would weaken White’s pawn formation unnecessarily.} 13...a5 {Securing space on the queenside and preventing anyideas of b2-b4 from White. Grabbing the pawn with 13... “\fxe4 would have been inadvisable, as} 14.Be2 {?OCR} { (better than 14. 0xe4 ®xe4 15. 2xe4 c5!, equalizing in AOObhukov- V.Tseshkovsky, Belorechensk 1993)} 14...Qxe4 15.Bd2 {forces Black to give up his queen: 16... 4#/xel+ 17. 8xel Bxel+ 18. 2xel &xd4 19. 2c3 &xc3 20. W%xc3 &xh3 21. 4%b4 and White’s queen out- maneuvered Black’s rook and bishop to mop up the queenside pawns in L.Shamkovich-C.Baljon, Amsterdam 1979; Ippolito-M.Fitzko, New York 1993; and Ippolito-J.Wheat, Bloom- ington 1997. 14. 8ad1 c7?! ie ik 2 jj a or Ba oAuT ie" DY, Wi NK Black “corrects” the placement of his queen, but this is a tactical error. Better is the more common 14... fd7, with the idea of playing ...Ac5-a6 and ..2d7-c5, perhaps with an eye toward the ...f7-f5 strike. 15. 4db5! A pseudo-sacrifice to break through on dé.} 15...b5 16.cxb5 {?OCR} Qe7 {Of course not 16... %b6??} 17.Nxc6 {?OCR} {trapping the queen. 17. Axd6 Black’s knight on c5 is now hanging. White will get a rook and two strong pawns for his two knights, which in this case proves decisive.} 17...Ne6 18.Ne5 {?OCR} Nd7 19.Ne4 {?OCR} Bxe5 {?OCR} 20.f4 {Black’s bishops are boxed in and he is still low on space. To ensure victory, White just needs to take control of the dark squares and break through along the d-file and on the kingside.} 20...Rf8 21.g4 {Threatening f4-f5.} 21...Ng7 {Or 21... 2c5} {ERROR: 42} {with the contin- ued threat of £4-f5.} 22.Nf2 {?OCR} {Ab8 Black is attempting to play ...ab8- c6 to shield his b7-pawn from the bishop on g2. 23. 2¢5 The most straightforward way to penetrate the dark squares is to ex- change bishops. 23... ANc6 24. 2d6 2e6 25. b3 Wc8 26. 2xf8 Wxf8 27. 2e4 Be8 28. f5 2c8 29. e6! White has been building up for this breakthrough. 29... fxe6? Stiffer resistance would have been put up by 29... gxf5 30. gxf5 fxe6 31. f6 Nh5 (not 31... Nf5? 32. 28xf5 exf5 33. Wg3+ &f7 34. hxe8 &xe8 35. 47, when White is winning) 32. 2f1 Wf7, when White still has a large advantage thanks to his superior mobility but is by no means completely winning. 30. f6 The black knight on g7 is trapped. It didn’t take many inaccuracies from Black in this game for him to find himselfin trouble. Wojo’s 15. @db5! il- lustrates an important tactical theme that players of both White and Black should remember. In the next game, we see the same motif of a knight landing on b5.} 1-0

