1.Nf3 Nf6 2.c4 d6 3.d4 g6 4.g3 Bg7 5.Bg2 O-O 6.O-O Nbd7 7.Nc3 e5 8.e4 c6 9.Rb1 {A“Wojo Weapon” that allows White to get the kind of positional game that he is looking for, without stepping into a sea of complications. Placing the rook on bl takes the sting out of Black’s tactical shots early on: his rook is off the al-h8 diagonal, and his b-pawn is defended against any ...%d8-b6 sortie. Meanwhile, the rook is useful on bl because it helps prepare the gradual b2-b3-b4 push later in the middle- game. The disadvantage of this move is that it may not be useful for White if Black doesn’t concede the center with} 9...exd4 {and instead goes about prepar- ing the ...b7-b5 punch with something like 9... a6. We look at this type of ap- proach for Black in Chapter 4. 9... exd4} 10.Nxd4 Re8 11.h3 Nc5 {Black can try to take advantage of White’s “slow” move 9 with 11... ab6!?} 12.b3 d5 {a break in the center which has been tried a handful of times. After} 13.exd5 cxd5 {ERROR: c5,} {White retains his edge: 14... abd7} 14.b4 a5 15.a3 {gave White the upper hand in F.Sage-C. Vasile, corr. 2004, while 14... de4!? 15. Axe4 dxe4 16. 4b5 gives White a large initiative. 12. 8e1 a5 13. b3 This patient approach is the best one. White prevents any attempt at ...a9-a4 from Black: he can now sim- ply push past with b3-b4, dislodging Black’s knight from c5. White is also slowly removing his pieces from the al-h8 diagonal. 13... Afd7 Black prepares for some maneu- vering. 13... h6, a waiting move, has also been tried. White usually piles up on the d6-pawn with 14. 2f4, after which he has a comfortable game. 14. 2e3 Df6?! Now it becomes apparent that Black is just going back and forth. More common is 14... 4e5 15. 4c2 We7 16. 2bd1 “ed7 17. f4 and so on, when again it seems like Black isn’t making any progress. 15. W%c2 We7 16. kbd1 2d7 17. 2f4 White is fully developed, so he de- cides to turn the screws on d6. Black, who has lost two moves by playing ...@f6-d7 and back again, will be hard- pressed to find an adequate defense. 17... 2ad8 nN ay, bn \ Bo» > 1 Weed ~ WY \\ B® \ Vo NN WN N N SN = Rais, | AN ISX ws Ww Do Y; q AB Y N E NS SS \ pe NN SS [ne |\ml SYS Nt zzz 18. adb5! Using the same tactical theme we saw in the previous game. 18... cxb5 19. 2xd6 We6 20. 2xc5 White has, for the moment, won a pawn. Amazingly, this exact position has occurred at least twice in practice. 20... 2c8 21. 2d4 White prepares e4-e5. The reaso- nable 21. 2d6 was attempted in M.Luch- M.Stolz, Czech Republic 2004, but after 21... bxc4, White blundered with 22. b4!? Bc6 23. e5?? (23. Ab5 instead, threatening “b5-c7, would have left Black in trouble) , when after 23... 2xd6 24. exd6 Yxel+ 25. 8xel Bxel+ 26. 2h2 axb4 27. 0d5 @xd5 28. 2xd5 c3 it was Black who had all the play and who went on to win. 21... bxce4 22. e5 exb3 Mon VTP Laan VERITAS OTTTT OTITT sees, 22... 0h5 23. Wd2! would likely have done little to change the result. 23. Wd2! White covers the f4 square in prepa- ration for trapping Black’s knight. 23... Dh5 24. 24 White now wins material — and with it, the game. 24... 2c6 25. axb3 Aclean conversion. There was noth- ing wrong with 25. gxh5 &xg2 26. xg2 bxa2 and so on, but Wojo prefers the least messy solution. 25... 2xg2 26. exg2 Exc3 26... %c6+ 27. 221 f6 is suggested by the computers as a last-ditch attempt to save Black, but after 28. e6 (28. gxh5? fxe5 would let Black back in the game) 28... f5 29. 2xg7 Axg7 30. 4d5, White’s position is overpowering. 27. 2xc3 Wc6+ 28. eg¢1 Af4 29. Yxf4 Yxc3 30. e6 fxe6 31. 2xe6 A final tactical finesse. 31... 2f8 32. We3 Wxe3 33. fxe3 b5 34. 2d5 2b8 35. 28a6 &2c3 36. 2ad6 ©f7 37. 2d8 2b6 38. 25d6 After White forces the trade of rooks, it’s all over. White’s prophylactic 9. 8b1 avoids many of the tactical ideas players of the black pieces like to employ. Even though the rook had to move again with 16. 8bd1 in order to come to the center, this slight loss of time didn’t mean much compared to the time Black lost with the ill-fated ... “f6-d7- f6 shuffle. In this game, White slowly gained the upper hand just by putting his pieces on good squares and eyeing the d6-pawn. Once again, the tactical shot @d4-b5 arose, ruining Black’s position. In the next game, Wojo must slowly force his grandmaster opponent back by taking space on both sides of the board before he is allowed to harvest the d6-pawn. This game was first an- notated in Jonathan Hilton’s original “How Wojo Won’ series for Chess Life Online (see Part III, published April 2007) , and it reappears here with the notes significantly revised.} 1-0

