1.Nf3 Nf6 2.c4 g6 3.g3 Bg7 4.Bg2 O-O 5.d4 d6 6.O-O Nbd7 7.Nc3 e5 8.e4 c6 9.Rb1 a5 10.h3 Re8 11.Re1 exd4 12.Nxd4 Nc5 13.b3 Qe7 14.Re2 {K//2 Y nein A useful waiting move, preparing to put pressure on the d-pawn with an eventual 2c1-f4 and #e2-d2. Note that Black was lining up along the e-file. With 14. 8e2, White places his rook on a square where it is defended by his two knights, preventing any tactical ideas from Black involving ...d6-d5. 14. 2f4 first is somewhat more common, when only after} 14...Nfd7 {?OCR} {is} 15.Reb2 {?OCR} {played. Then} 15...Ne5 16.Be3! {ERROR: allows} {White to hit Black’s knight back with f2-f4 fol- lowed by &e3-f2. 14... 2d7 15. 2f4 Dh5 16. 2e3 White has succeeded in luring Black’s knight out to the awkward h5 square.} 16...Rd8 17.Qd2 Qf8 18.Rd1 Re8 {?OCR} 19.Qe2 {Overprotecting the e4-pawn will be important in the struggle for control of the kingside.} 19...h6 20.Kh2 {?OCR} f6 {ERROR: 21} {Ah5S 22 feel Yh7 23. a3 Black has maneuvered all of his pieces to the kingside, so Wojo turns his attention to the queenside. The absence of Black’s knight on h5 from the activity in the center, along with his rook being on d8 (rather than on a8) and his queen on f8 (rather than c7) will make it hard for him to defend against White’s impending b3-b4-b5 expansion. 23... 4h8 Black begins an interesting attempt to generate counterplay. Anticipat- ing White’s idea of advancing to b4 and b5, Black exerts pressure on the queenside dark squares, which White must leave behind in order to carry on with his plans. 24. b4 axb4 25. axb4 Dab 26. b5 White begins to break down Black’s position by undermining the d5 square. 26... Ab4 27. 4b3 c5 28. ade2 (hee ee ww LL Z 28... f5 Black has succeeded in plugging up the queenside, stymying White’s attack there. Now, he seeks counterplay on the kingside to relieve his cramped position. His d6-pawn remains weak, however. As White continues to push for more space, Black will find it harder and harder to hold his backward d- pawn. Wojo begins by doubling on the d-file. 29,.8d2 Af6 30. 8ed1 WS 31. exf5 &xf5 32. ¢4 White continues to gain space. Having forced Black to defend d6, White switches his attention to slowly advancing on the kingside. One of his main ideas is the knight maneuver e2-f4, further controlling d5. 32... 2e4 33. 0f4 &xg2 34. kxg2 Black’s position has seemed more or less defensible up to this point, but now Black struggles with the pressure on his position. How can he defend both his g6-pawn ( against White’s upcoming “b3-b1 ) and his d6-pawn ( against White’s powerful doubled rooks ) ? Unfortunately, at this point there is no good answer. For instance, on 34... 2e4 Black has to face possible tactics involving “f4xg6, followed by a pin along the b1-h7 diagonal. 34... 25 Frustrated, Black lashes out. Now White simply regroups and takes ad- vantage of the newly created outposts on f5 and h5. 35. Dfe2 We7 36. 4g3 Wed 37. 0f5 White is getting closer and closer to his goal of winning the d6-pawn. 37... 2f8 38. f3 White methodically prepares to put his bishop on the h2-b8 diagonal. 38... b6 39. 221 We6 40. 8h2 &g8 There was nothing better. The d6- pawn could not be saved. 41. 2xd6 Oh5 42. 4e4 “ ai ‘E Wek G Vera A Following the collapse of the d- pawn, White lays waste to Black’s entire position. The rest is a mopup operation on the kingside. 42... 2xd6 43. 8xd6 Of4+ 44. Hf1 Rxd6 45. 8xd6 We5 46. Wd1 Deb6 47. 8d7 &h8 48. Axh6 Wh2 49. 4f7+ &g7 50. 0fxg5+ &g6 51. 0xe6 Wxh3+ 52. eg1 8xe6 53. Wb1 Wh6 54. 4d6+ 1-0 White’s cautious play in the early middlegame paid off. Although some of his maneuvers shuffling back and forth may have seemed a little eccen- tric, his 23. a3 and 24. b4 ultimately caught Black off-guard. With space- taking moves like 26. b5 and 32. 94, White was able to push Black back. Eventually, Black had too little ma- neuvering room to adequately defend his backward d-pawn. As is par for the course, the fall of this pawn meant Black’s rapid demise. Depending on the amount of resis- tance Black puts up, White may not have to wait all the way to move 41 to see the black d-pawn fall. When Black is an amateur rather than a grand- master, his position can deteriorate far more quickly. In the last game of this section, we admire the speed with which Black’s fortress crumbles in the hands of a non-master.)} *

