1.Nf3 d6 2.d4 g6 3.g3 Bg7 4.Bg2 Nf6 5.c4 O-O 6.O-O c6 7.Nc3 Qe8 {?OCR} {It is somewhat unusual for Black to commit his queen to this square so early. Normally, Black tries to stay more flexible with the Lady.} 8.h3 Nbd7 9.e4 e5 10.Be3 Rb8 {?OCR} 11.Bc1 {?OCR} {Because Black has already showed his hand by bringing the queen to c7 and not b6, White can comfortably slide the rook over to cl instead. 1l...exd4 12. Axd4 Ac5 13. %c2 We7 Note that Black seems unsure as to the placement of his queen. More to the point was 13... a5. 14. 2fel 2e6 EK] A ae bade This, too, seems overly committal. Better was to stay flexible with 14... a5, not committing to any particular piece configuration. 15. b3 Zad8 16. 2cd1 Preparing the traditional assault in the center. 16... a5 17. f4 &c8 Although this configuration with the bishop on c8 and the queen’s rook on d8 is tempting, Black will suffer from the inability of his pieces to de- fend the queenside. 18. 2f2 Wf8 19. a3 Dab Anticipating b3-b4. 20. 8b1 Ze7 21. %d2 White targets the loose a5-pawn. 21... Ac7 Black reroutes his knight, but no one can say to where. 22. Ac2 Preparing for a possible 2f2-b6. Black can do embarrassingly little to defend his b6 square. 22... ked7 23. Ha4 White has too many threats. The a5-pawn is even hanging. 23... b5 24. Ab6 Be7 25. 4xc8 Rxc8 26. W%xd6 Taking the d6-pawn and thus put- ting an end to its misery. 26... We8 27. e5 Re6 28. 4% d2 Ad7 29. 4d4 In Wojtkiewicz-Werner, White had no trouble gaining the advantage. Black found himself forced to play ...2a8-d8 and ...2d7-c8 in order to defend the d6- pawn, a maneuver which left his queenside vulnerable. After 23. 0a4, Black’s position collapsed. Conclusion: In all four of the above games, something went dreadfully wrong for Black. Either he made an inaccuracy or two that allowed White to crash through on d6, or he was slowly pushed off the board and forced to cede the d-pawn, or both. With patience and a keen eye for penetrating weaknesses in Black’s position, Wojo was able to convert his space advantage into something more tangible. White Breaks Through on the Kingside When Black successfully finds a way to defend his d6-pawn, White must cre- ate — as the old saying goes — a “second weakness.” Often, weaknesses on the queenside — such as the a5-pawn or the b6 square — prove sufficient for White to penetrate Black’s position. But when Black proves solid, White often begins expanding on the kingside (much as in Wojtkiewicz-Shulman above, only earlier in the middlegame) as a way to increase his influence over the board. Wojo’s formula for victory using such an approach was straightforward: first, tie Black to the defense of the d6- pawn; then, advance the pawns on the kingside. In order to accomplish the first goal, he would bring his queen’s rook to di and then, after shoring up his e4-pawn by way of &fl-el, f2-f4, and &e3-f2, gently slide his queen overfromc2 to d2. From there, all that remained was to remove the knight from d4 in order to unleash White’s buildup along the d-file. In order to defend, Black would either have to play ...2c8-d7, ...2a8-d8, and ...2d7- c8 again (which, as we know from Wojtkiewicz-Werner above, weakens the a5-pawn) or tie himself down by putting his active king’s bishop on ei- ther f8 or e7. If Black chose the latter, Wojo had the “all clear” to begin an orderly assault on the kingside. Let’s begin with a typical example.} 1-0

