1.Nf3 Nf6 2.c4 g6 3.g3 Bg7 4.Bg2 O-O 5.O-O d6 6.d4 Nbd7 7.Nc3 e5 8.e4 c6 9.h3 Re8 {?OCR} 10.Be3 exd4 11.Nxd4 Nc5 12.Nce2 {?OCR} a5 13.Bd2 {?OCR} Nfd7 14.b3 Qe7 15.Re1 {?OCR} {Yj YEZ Z Aron 7 NG 4 GZ = Wt g a peo 8 Am} 15...Ne5 {The provocative ...4d7-e5, essen- tially begging for White to play f2-f4, is extremely common in practice. It is not good, however. Black is wasting time: 15... Af8, 15... 2a6 (preparing ...Ad7-c5 and even ...®a6-b4, and the space- gaining 15... h5 were all preferable. 16. f4 Ded7 17. 2f2 The standard maneuver begins. 17... 4f8 Black begins anticipating White’s assault on the d-pawn and seeks to defend it. 18. Ade2 &f6 19. 4d2 &e7 Black has succeeded in holding on to his d-pawn, but his position is far from auspicious. With his best pieces caught in a miserable tangle, there is little that Black can do to stop White’s impending kingside assault. 20. 24 ercren are a af, YY Bn a White, in accordance with his plan, begins the assault. His knight on e2 can come to g3, and the idea of h3-h4-h5 to open the h-file is in the works. 20... f6 21. Ag3 Wf7 Black eyes the c4-pawn. His idea is to break with ...a5-a4, making White’s queenside pawns a target. 22. 2f1 Cautious defense of c4. White need not take any chances. 22... b6 22... a4? would now of course be met by 23. b4 “a6 24. 4xa4, winning for White. 23. 2e3 &b7 24. 222 White decides it is more important that the bishop remain on the h1-a8 diagonal. 24... 2ad8 Wojo likely saw that he could meet 24... a4 with 25. b4 2a6 26. a3!, when 26... W/xc4 27. 4d5! shows off White’s well-coordinated pieces. If 27... cxd5, White wins the black queen with 28. 8c1 Wb3 ( or 28... 4b5 29. 2f1 ) 29. 8c3. Should White have failed to see all this, the alternative 26. b5 cxb5 27. 0xb5 Yxc4 28. 2f1 Wf7 29. 4xd6 would prob- ably also give White a slight advantage. 25. Wf2 Eb8 26. 2f3 Lh8 27. %g2 White is preparing for a kingside assault. 27... 2a8 28. h4 &b7 29. h5 &g7 30. Zh1 Black, who has nothing better to do than twiddle his thumbs, cannot gen- erate any real counterplay to White’s steady buildup. 30... 2h8 31. %b2 Ebg8 32. a3 Now that Black has dedicated his entire army to resisting on the king- side, White simply prepares the stan- dard queenside breakthrough. 32... 8a8 33. Wc2 White guards the a4 andc4 squares in preparation for b3-b4. Note White’s patience. Now Black cracks under pressure. 33... a4?! This pawn push is the beginning of the end. Black’s defensive setup soon crumbles on all fronts. 34. b4 Ab3 35. 8e2!? 35. h6+ £8 36. Axa4 Bxa4 37. xb3 would have ended matters immedi- ately, as Black’s rook is stuck on h8 and cannot get to the queenside. Instead, Wojo continues his slow grind, not yet willing to give up on the idea of open- ing the h-file. From here on out, Black does succeed in mobilizing his forces somewhat, allowing him to obtain a degree of counterplay. 5... 8he8 36. 4xa4 &xa4 37. 4xb3 Bca8 38. 2c1 b5 39. %c3 ¢5 Black finally launches an attack in the center in an attempt for counter- play, but White already has a decisive upper hand. 40. hxg6 hxg6 41. cxb5 &c8 42. We3 cxb4 43. axb4 &xb4 44. 2a3 Rb3 45. 8d3 2xb5 46. 2xd6 Gia FS pao nayy ae M) “wa bay Ce BViny AV , { \ P ate: ale G Ai a White has emerged up a pawn — and, notsurprisingly, it was Black’s d6- pawn that ultimately fell. To his credit, however, Black has finally succeeded in developing all of his pieces. White does win, but converting his pawn advantage requires strong technique. 46... 2b2 47. 2hd1 Ac5 48. 2xc5 &xe5 49. 81d2 Xec2 50. 8xc2 Bxc2 51. 2d7 2£c6 52. 8a7 Sa2 53. 8ce7 &2b5? By removing his bishop from the h1-a8 diagonal, Black allows White to make a decisive central strike. 34. e5! Ending Black’s resistance. 54... 2xe2 55. exf6+ &g8 There was nothing better. 56. axe2 Wd5+ Black squirms to get out of the sev- enth-rank pin, but White has already won too many pawns. 57. f2 &f8 58. 2c8 Baé Or 58... W/f7 59. We7!. 59. 2xf8+ This game is a typical example of how Wojo would use an effective kingside pawn storm to wear Black down in this line. He began by tying Black down to the d6-pawn, but after that, he expanded with g3-g4, ®e2-g3, 292-f3, &g1-g2, and h3-h4-h5. Black cracked under the pressure and went down a pawn. Then, in the end, White broke through to Black’s king in any case, eventually securing mate with 59. Bxf8+. The following game reiterates these themes. Black’s defense is somewhat less stubborn and White’s attack comes more quickly, however.} 1-0

