k. Perhaps White was worried about 32... d5!? instead, but then 33. cxd5 cxd5 34. 2xd5 &xf5 35. 2f2 Yxh3 (not 35... W%xg5 36. 8xe5) 36. Wxh3 &2xh3 37. 8xe5 &f8 38. kxe8 Bxe8 39. 2xb7 would leave White up a pawn. 32... W£6 33. 25 White’s idea. The endgame that follows is indeed better for White, but not necessarily by much. 33... Wxg5 34. Wxg5 &xg5 35. 2xd6 Ef8 36. 226 Se ‘= jae “a su, re (ji ( 6 a 7, i Zi — 36... 228?! Black can maintain the balance with 36... 2f4, when White’s f5-pawn is in trouble. Then 37. f6 8e6 ( 37... &xh3 38. 2e3! breaks down Black’s piece coordination ) 38. 2e3, continuing to crack open the kingside, leaves White with just a tiny pull. 37. 8xg8+ &xg8 38. 8d1 White prevents Black from develop- ing with ...2c8-d7. Once again, White will go back to penetrating on the king- side shortly: with Black paralyzed for the meantime, White intends #g1-h1 and #d1-g1. 38... 2f7 39. fh1 2e7 39... %f6 40. 2d6+ instead looks dismal. 40. 2e3 h4 41. 2h2 @e8 42. 2821 £7 43. 8d1 he8 44. 22 17iuee 1G ei aa me a 5 2 i A GTITICE VAISS T 4 GFAITF C8 Gs E27 7 White is toying with his prey. Li 44... 2f7 45. f3 &f6 46. 2g1 2d7 There is now finally a clear route to victory. Blackis helpless to prevent the kingside penetration. 47. 2¢5+ &f7 48. 2xe7 &xe7 49. 8g7+ &d6 50. c5+ &c7 51. 6 Bf8 52. 8f5 Bxf6 53. 8xd7+ 1-0 In this game, White’s well organized forces tied Black down to the defense of the d-pawn early on. The standard maneuver f2-f4, 2e3-f2, ®d4-e2, and Wc2-d2 was executed by White without any serious opposition from Black. White was able to convert his pressure ( by way of moves such as 23. @xe6 and 25. f5 ) into a promising kingside attack, which he botched by backing down from 32. 95. Inthe endgame, Black had some chances to defend, but ultimately White’s continued kingside pressure ( and Black’s lack of queenside develo pment ) allowed White to break through to the last three ranks. Conclusion: When Black is chained to the defense of his d-pawn, White often has the possibility of expanding on the kingside. After completing development, players of White should be looking for kingside pawn storm ideas. Ultimately, however, White should remember that his power comes from his control of the center and his extra space on both sides of the board. A timely a2-a3 and b3- b4 thrust can do just as much to disrupt Black’s defenses as running down the white h-pawn. A Classic Revisited Despite the apparent simplicity of White’s formula for tying Black down to d6, by the time Wojo actually em- ployed it beginning in the 1980s and 90s, it was already several decades in the making. It is worth briefly revisiting the classic game Stahlberg-Boleslavsky from the Zurich Candidates’ Tourna- ment of 1953, to see how much players of White have learned since the old days. The following game — which was phenomenally annotated by Bronstein in the Zurich 1953 tournament book ( perhaps the first great work written “about” the King’s Indian Defense ) — had a profound impact on the en- tire line with ...Ab8-d7, ...e7-e5, and ...e5xd4, so much so that we have dubbed Black’s setup here the “Zurich 1953 Defense” for the purposes of this book. In it, we see White struggling with uncomfortable pressure on the queenside. Stahlberg, Gideon Boleslavsky, Isaak [E69] Candidates’ Tournament, Zurich 1953 1. d4 Of6 2. c4 g6 3. 23 827 4. 222 0-0 5. 4c3 d6 6. 4f3 Abd7 7. 0-0 e5 8. e4 Ze8 9. h3 exd4 10. 4xd4 4c5 11. 8e1 a5 12. %c2 It is worth mentioning that this does not hang the e4-pawn to 12... “fxe4, as 13. Axe4 &xd4 14. 825 Wd7 ( not 14... f6? 15. 2xf6 ) 15. Af6+ &xf6 16. 2xf6 He6 17. 2c3 is known to give White excellent compensation on the dark squares. Although the text move remained the main line for many years, it has the drawback of allowing Black to play the space-gaining ...a5-a4. Wojo would simply play the more modern 12. 2b1 instead, when 12... a4 could be met by 13. Adb5 &d7 14. 2f4 with pressure. For instance, T.Markowski-A.Mista, Warsaw2004, went 14... 2xb5 15. cxb5! &fd7 16. ¥4c2, when White had the two bishops, more space, and a slightly more active game.)} *

